      "message": "[Critical] Line 319: transformSwarmMessages() holds mtx_ while invoking ChatHandler::transformSwarmMessages(), which is plugin-controlled code. Other changes in this patch explicitly avoid calling plugin callbacks while holding this mutex because callbacks can invoke services that reacquire mtx_, so this reintroduces a deadlock path during message loading. Snapshot the enabled handlers under the lock, release it, then invoke the handlers.\n```suggestion\n    std::vector\u003cChatHandler*\u003e handlersToTransform;\n    {\n        std::lock_guard const lk(mtx_);\n        std::pair\u003cstd::string, std::string\u003e const key(accountId, conversationId);\n        const auto toggledIt \u003d chatHandlerToggled_.find(key);\n        const auto allowIt \u003d allowDenyList_.find(key);\n        for (auto\u0026 handler : chatHandlers_) {\n            const auto handlerName \u003d handler-\u003egetChatHandlerDetails().at(\"name\");\n            const bool toggled \u003d toggledIt !\u003d chatHandlerToggled_.end()\n                                 \u0026\u0026 toggledIt-\u003esecond.contains(reinterpret_cast\u003cuintptr_t\u003e(handler.get()));\n            const bool allowed \u003d allowIt !\u003d allowDenyList_.end()\n                                 \u0026\u0026 allowIt-\u003esecond.contains(handlerName)\n                                 \u0026\u0026 allowIt-\u003esecond.at(handlerName);\n            if (toggled || allowed)\n                handlersToTransform.push_back(handler.get());\n        }\n    }\n    for (auto* handler : handlersToTransform)\n        handler-\u003etransformSwarmMessages(messages, accountId, conversationId);\n```",
